  "prompt": "Does the law prohibit money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, the law prohibits money laundering in virtually all jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering is the process of making illegally gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). It typically involves three stages: placement, layering, and integration. The specific laws and penalties vary by country, but the prohibition is a global standard.\n\n### Key Legal Frameworks:\n1. **United States**: The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970, the USA PATRIOT Act, and the Money Laundering Control Act of 1986 criminalize money laundering and require financial institutions to report suspicious activities.\n\n2. **European Union**: The EU has implemented several Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Directives, which member states must transpose into national law, requiring enhanced due diligence and reporting obligations.\n\n3. **United Kingdom**: The Proceeds of Crime Act 2002 (POCA) and the Money Laundering Regulations 2017 are the primary legal frameworks combating money laundering.\n\n4. **International Cooperation**: The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing, which many countries adopt into their legal systems.\n\n### Penalties:\nPenalties for money laundering can be severe, including:\n- Fines (often in the millions or even billions of dollars)\n- Imprisonment (ranging from several years to life sentences)\n- Asset forfeiture (confiscation of illegally obtained assets)\n\n### Enforcement:\nGovernments work in collaboration with financial institutions, law enforcement agencies, and international organizations to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is a serious crime with significant legal consequences worldwide.",
